China Stocks: Guoyuan Securities, Jiangxi Copper, China Vanke

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-04-14T07:37:28Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-14/icbc-citic-securities-sinopec-guoyuan-china-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual price changes in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 3 p.m. close.  The Shanghai Composite Index fell 0.3 percent to 3,042.64.
The  CSI 300 Index (SHSZ300)  lost 0.6 percent to 3,353.56.  Copper producers: Jiangxi Copper Co. (600362 CH), the
nation’s biggest producer of the metal, retreated 1 percent to
39.58 yuan. Tongling Nonferrous Metals Group Co. (000630 CH)
slipped 0.6 percent to 28.80 yuan.  Goldman Sachs Group Inc. lowered its year-end copper
forecast by 11 percent on concern that weak Chinese demand and
the deadly earthquake in  Japan  will delay an expected reduction
in exchange stockpiles.  Developers: China Vanke Co. (000002 CH), the nation’s
largest developer, declined 1.5 percent to 8.80 yuan. Poly Real
Estate Group Co. (600048 CH) lost 2.3 percent to 13.83 yuan.  Moody’s Investors Service lowered its outlook for China’s
property sector to “negative” from “stable” on concern
residential sales could decline by as much as 30 percent as
local government enforce housing curbs.  Shenzhen may announce
new measures to curb  home prices , 21st Century Business Herald
reported today, citing an unidentified real estate developer.  Power companies: Shanghai Electric Power Co. (600021 CH)
sank 1.2 percent to 5.02 yuan. Guangdong Electric Power
Development Co. (000539 CH) dropped 1.7 percent, the biggest
decline since March 11, to 6.42 yuan.  Electricity demand rose 13 percent last month from a year
earlier to 388.8 billion kilowatt-hours, the National Energy
Administration said in a statement on its website today. That
compares with February’s 16 percent increase.  Citic Securities Co. (600030 CH) advanced 0.6 percent, the
most in a week, to 14.62 yuan. Shareholders of China’s largest
securities company by market value approved the company’s plan
for a Hong Kong initial public offering.  Guoyuan Securities Co. (000728 CH) slid 1.5 percent to
13.21 yuan, the biggest loss since March 30. The brokerage’s
first-quarter profit fell 3.3 percent from the same period a
year earlier to 254 million yuan, according to a statement to
the Shenzhen Stock Exchange today.  Shenzhen Development Bank Co. (000001)  (000001 CH) added 0.8 percent
to 18.19 yuan, the highest since Nov. 11. The bank’s first
quarter net income may rise as much as 60 percent from a year
earlier to 2.52 billion yuan, according to a statement to the
Shenzhen Stock Exchange.  --Irene Shen,  Michael Wei . Editor: Allen Wan  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
